*top** instance of that line to include everything you need in one long string.**Change this:**`GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX_DEFAULT="quiet splash resume=UUID=d89b0ade-9f73-4eb1-ba82-5792324cfcbc"`**To this:**```bashGRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX_DEFAULT="quiet splash resume=UUID=d89b0ade-9f73-4eb1-ba82-5792324cfcbc mem_sleep_default=deep mitigations=off zswap.enabled=1"```**Step 4:** Save and Apply.1.  Press `Ctrl+O`, then `Enter` to save.2.  Press `Ctrl+X` to exit.3.  **Crucial Step:** Update GRUB to apply the changes.    ```bash    sudo update-grub    ```4.  Reboot your computer.-----### 3\. How to Improve Performance Further (Kubuntu Specifics)Since you are on Kubuntu (KDE Plasma) with an older Dual-Core i5, here are three specific changes that will help more than the kernel flags:#### A. Disable "Baloo" (File Indexing)KDE's file search indexer (Baloo) is notorious for eating CPU on dual-core laptops.1.  Open **System Settings**.2.  Search for **File Search**.3.  Uncheck "Enable File Search".    *Result: Instant reduction in background CPU usage.*#### B. Speed up AnimationsThis makes the system *feel* faster.1.  Open **System Settings** -\> **Workspace Behavior** -\> **General Behavior**.2.  Set "Animation speed" to **Instant** or slide the bar to the far right.#### C. Optimize SwappinessSince you have 16GB RAM, you don't want Linux writing to the disk swap unless it absolutely has to. Default is usually 60 (swaps when RAM is 40% full).1.  Check current value: `cat /proc/sys/vm/swappiness`2.  To set it to 10 (only swap when RAM is 90% full):    ```bash    sudo nano /etc/sysctl.conf    ```3.  Add this line to the bottom:    ```text    vm.swappiness=10    ```4.  Save (`Ctrl+O`, `Enter`) and Exit.### Summary CheckIf you apply the GRUB change I provided above, you will be running:1.  Hibernate/Resume (Supported)2.  Deep Sleep fix (Supported)3.  Mitigations OFF (Speed boost, lower security)4.  Zswap ON (Memory efficiency)*